{"type":"message","id":"037582f7","parentId":"df6a8a21","timestamp":"2026-03-21T09:53:26.562Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The problem is clear now: breadth is NaN because the history data for 2026-03-10 is not available (the history CSV might not extend that far). Let me check what dates are in the history file.\n\nWait, the previous version of the script worked and got breadth=0.4856. But now with the new version it gets NaN. The difference is that in the previous version, I computed `hist[\"ma20_stock\"]` BEFORE filtering by trade_date, and then filtered after. But in the new version, I'm computing on `history_df[history_df[\"trade_date\"] <= trade_date]`.\n\nActually wait, looking at the old code more carefully:\n\n\nThe old approach computed rolling means across all historical data grouped by stock, then filtered down to the target date. My new version is filtering first and then computing the rolling means on that filtered subset, which is why I'm getting NaN values—I don't have enough lookback data within the filtered window.\n\nThe real issue is that the script was already working with breadth=0.4856 and a neutral regime, but now it's returning NaN for breadth with the new implementation. The old code was doing the rolling computation on the full history before any date filtering, so it had the necessary lookback period. My revised approach broke that by filtering too early in the pipeline. The NaN in the debug output suggests the data isn't being loaded correctly or the date filtering is happening before the rolling window can accumulate enough data points. The rolling mean calculation might not have enough historical data before 2026-03-10 to compute a proper 20-day window, which is why the breadth value is NaN. I should compute the rolling means on the full history first, then filter down to the target date like the old code did, and also check what dates are actually present in the dataset.","thinkingSignature":"656596a00ae9db9e80f5adf86e26a78d225dce7377fa7e06041e9a5fff45ca11"},{"type":"text","text":"\nbreadth 变成 NaN 了——滚动窗口在全量历史前计算 vs 先过滤再计算导致数据不足。修复：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lun4r75qj9kb_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/generate_day1_3_mean_reversion_signals.py","old_string":"    # Indicator 2: MA20 breadth (% of stocks above their 20-day MA)\n    hist = history_df[history_df[\"trade_date\"] <= trade_date].copy()\n    g = hist.groupby(\"ts_code\", group_keys=False)\n    hist[\"ma20_stock\"] = g[\"close\"].transform(lambda s: s.rolling(20, min_periods=10).mean())\n    latest = hist[hist[\"trade_date\"] == trade_date].copy().dropna(subset=[\"ma20_stock\"])\n    breadth = float((latest[\"close\"] > latest[\"ma20_stock\"]).mean()) if len(latest) >= 50 else 0.5","new_string":"    # Indicator 2: MA20 breadth (% of stocks above their 20-day MA)\n    # Compute rolling on FULL history (needed for adequate lookback), then filter to date\n    hist_full = history_df.copy()\n    g = hist_full.groupby(\"ts_code\", group_keys=False)\n    hist_full[\"ma20_stock\"] = g[\"close\"].transform(lambda s: s.rolling(20, min_periods=10).mean())\n    hist = hist_full[hist_full[\"trade_date\"] <= trade_date]\n    latest = hist[hist[\"trade_date\"] == trade_date].copy().dropna(subset=[\"ma20_stock\"])\n    breadth = float((latest[\"close\"] > latest[\"ma20_stock\"]).mean()) if len(latest) >= 50 else 0.5"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":64563,"output":779,"cacheRead":24939,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":90281,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774086787508}}
